Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores the Telco customer churn data set from Kaggle. This data consists of 7043 customers described by 21 variables and can be found here - https://www.kaggle.com/blastchar/telco-customer-churn

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 7032 rows with 21 variables. The majority of the variables are boolean yes / no. Senior citizen was inconsistently coded as 1 / 0 in comparison to the other variables that were yes / no. Aside from gender there are three categorical variables InternetService [Fiber optic, DSL, No], Contract [Month to Month, Two year, One year], and PaymentMethod [Electronic check, Mailed check, Bank transfer (auto), Credit card (auto)].

Contract by duration [Month to Month, One year, Two year]

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in identifying which features correlate with long tenure and high lifetime value .

I am secondly interested in identifying which features correlate with churn.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that for both predictions above, contract will be the most important factor, and maybe also the number of services, and bill size.

Contract - Month to month contract is by far the most common customer type while I assume that one and two year contracts are associated with a lower rate of churn.
gender - is roughly equally distributed
SenioreCitizen - Roughly 1/7th of the population are senior citizens.

MultipleLines - roughly 3/7ths

TechSupport - Roughly 1/3rd of customers have tech support
OnlineBackup - Roughly 1/3rd of customers have online backup
PaperlessBilling - Roughly 3 in 7 customers use paperless billing
OnlineSecurity - Roughly 1 in three customers uses online security

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

TotalCharges distribution was highly right skewed with the majority of customers having very little totalCharges. Because of this, I performed a logistic transformation. After transforming the x axis, there appears to be a left skewed multimodal distribution.

Tenure distribution was very interesting with there being a peak at new customers and another peak at the tail with longtime customers.

When accounting for the tenure duration difference between churned and not churned, Contract - in particular Month to month comes to mind as a variable that is more likely to churn than not. This along with partner, dependents, and InternetService appear to be good variables to investigate further into whether or not they affect churn.

Monthly charges distribution appeared to be interesting as when the bins are set to narrow ranges, small pockets appear.

I will bin the monthly expenses into a categorical value Low, Med, High, and Very high to assist in my analysis.

I will create an additional variable and calculate the tenure in years

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were customers with 0 TotalCharges - I removed these data points as it wasnt entirely clear why they did not pay anything, in this instance I decided it was safer to remove them.

In [21]:
'''
I will bin the months into the following bins

Monthly Bins:
Low - $0-45 per month
Med - $45-75 per month
High - $75-100 per month
Very High - $100-150 per month
'''

bins = [0,45,75,100,150]
bin_names = ['Low', 'Med', 'High', 'Very High']

ordered_bill = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=bin_names)

df['monthly_bins'] = pd.cut(df.MonthlyCharges.astype(int), bins=bins, labels=bin_names).astype(ordered_bill)

In [25]:
def plot_matrix(mask):
    '''Function to plot a 2x2 subplot for specified mask'''
    color = sns.color_palette()[0]
    mask = mask
    bins = np.arange(0, df[mask].tenure.max(), 2)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2, figsize = [12, 8])
    sns.countplot(data=df[mask], x='Partner', color=color, ax=ax[0, 0])
    sns.countplot(data=df[mask], x='InternetService', color=color, ax=ax[0, 1])
    sns.countplot(data=df[mask], x='Churn', color=color, ax=ax[1,0])
    ax[1,1].hist(data=df[mask], x='tenure', bins=bins, color=color);

Churn Ratio by Variable¶

gender - Interestingly, churn within gender is nearly identical to overall churn.
SeniorCitizen - Senior Citizens are more likely to churn than non seniors.
Partner - Those with partners are less likely to churn than single folks
Dependents - Those with dependents are less likely to churn than those without
PhoneService - those with phone service are just as likely to churn as overall population
MultipleLines - Churn is 3% higher in those with multiple lines
InternetService - Fiber Optic customers churn 16% more often than overall population, while DSL and No internet service churn less than the population.
OnlineSecurity - Customers with online security churn less than the overall population
OnlineBackup - Little difference between population
DeviceProtection - Litte difference between population
TechSupport - Those with tech support tend to churn less than the population
StreamingTv - Churn slightly higher rate than population
StreamingMovies - Churn at slightly higher rate than population
Contract - Month to month churns roughly 17% more often while one year and two year contract holders churn much less frequent
PaperlessBilling - Customers without paperless billing tend to churn less often than the population
PaymentMethod - Customers paying by electronic check are the most frequent churners while those with automatic payments are the least likely to churn.

# Customer survival rate 

time_series = df.tenure
events = df.encoded_churn

# create a kmf object
kmf = KaplanMeierFitter() 

## Fit the data into the model
kmf.fit(time_series, events, label='Churned Customers')

## Create an estimate
kmf.plot()
plt.title('Customer Retention')

plt.xticks(ticks=[12, 24, 36, 48, 60, 72]);

5% of the customers churn within the first month, and within the first year 15% of customers churn. By the sixth year, it is estimated that 40% of customers have churned.

# Contract survival rate

T = df.tenure
E = df.encoded_churn

group = df.Contract
monthly = (group == 'Month-to-month')
one = (group == 'One year')
two = (group == 'Two year')



## create a kmf object
kmf = KaplanMeierFitter() 

## Fit the data into the model
kmf.fit(T[monthly], E[monthly], label='Month to month')
a = kmf.plot()

kmf.fit(T[one], E[one], label='One year')
kmf.plot(ax=a)

kmf.fit(T[two], E[two], label='Two year')
kmf.plot(ax=a)


plt.title('Customer Retention')

plt.xticks(ticks=[12, 24, 36, 48, 60, 72]);

However, when we look at the survival function for each contract type, we can see that vs Month to month, one and two year contracts churn much less. By the 6th year, 90% of month to month customers have churned while One year is around 40%, and two year customers are around 5%.

# InternetService survival rate

T = df.tenure
E = df.encoded_churn

group = df['InternetService']
no_internet = (group == 'No')
dsl = (group == 'DSL')
fiber = (group == 'Fiber optic')



## create a kmf object
kmf = KaplanMeierFitter() 

## Fit the data into the model
kmf.fit(T[no_internet], E[no_internet], label='No Internet')
a = kmf.plot()

kmf.fit(T[dsl], E[dsl], label='DSL')
kmf.plot(ax=a)

kmf.fit(T[fiber], E[fiber], label='Fiber')
kmf.plot(ax=a)


plt.title('Customer Retention')

plt.xticks(ticks=[12, 24, 36, 48, 60, 72]);

And when viewing the survival function for Internet Service we can confirm with this estimation that Customers with no internet service are much less likely to churn than those with internet. By the 6th year, 10% of customers without internet are predicted to churn, while roughly 28% of DSL customers are predicted to churn. Whats most surprising is that clsoe to 60% of Fiber customers are predicted to churn by the 6th year.

T = df.tenure
E = df.encoded_churn

contract = df['Contract']
bins = df['monthly_bins']
phone = df['PhoneService']
internet = df['InternetService']

short_tenure = (contract == 'Month-to-month') & (bins == 'Low') & (phone == 'Yes') & (internet == 'DSL')
long_tenure = (contract == 'Two year') & (bins == 'Very High') & (phone == 'Yes') & (internet == 'Fiber optic')

kmf = KaplanMeierFitter() 


kmf.fit(T[short_tenure], E[short_tenure], label='Month to Month > Low Bill > Phone & DSL')
a = kmf.plot()

kmf.fit(T[long_tenure], E[long_tenure], label='Two year > Very high bill > Phone & Fiber optic')
kmf.plot(ax=a);

referencing the crosstab that identified churn rate within certain variables, we can see that customers that are month to month, have low bills and subscribe to both phone and dsl have the worst survival rate out of any other segment.
